<bdy>

The <b><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../133/6639133.xml">
economy</link> of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../540/66540.xml">
ancient Greece</link></b> was characterized by the extreme importance of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../627/627.xml">
agriculture</link>, all the more so because of the relative poverty of <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../108/12108.xml">
Greece</link></country>
's soil. Beginning in the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../840/34840.xml">
6th century B.C.</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../433/426433.xml">
craftsmanship</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../208/39208.xml">
commerce</link> (principally <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../323/18842323.xml">
maritime</link>) developed and became increasingly more important in the classical period. <p>

It should be noted that the idea of an "economy" as it is understood today is relatively <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../731/60731.xml">
anachronistic</link> when used to refer to ancient Greece. The Greek word <it>oikonomia</it> (οἰκονομία) designates mainly the <it>oikos</it> (οἶκος), meaning the home or hearth. Thus <skilled_worker wordnetid="110605985" confidence="0.8">
